				<text>7.4.5.2 (not in quiz): Gauss elimination method â”€ inverse of 3 x 3 matrix</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p></p>
<p>Use the Gauss elimination method to find the inverse of the following matrices</p>
<p>\[\bf A = {@A@},\] \[\bf B = {@B@}.\]</p>
<div>(a) \(\bf A^{-1}=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</div>
<p><br></p>
<div>(b) \(\bf B^{-1}=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</div>
<p></p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p></p><p><b>FEEDBACK</b></p><p>We can find the inverse of matrix \(\bf A\) using the Gaussian elimination method.<br></p><p>We do this by reducing the matrix \(\bf A\) to the identity matrix \(\bf I\).&nbsp;There is no unique procedure for this but here is one example.</p><p>We first place \(\bf A\) and \(\bf I\) adjacent to each other.<br></p><p></p><p>{@A@} {@I@}.</p><p>We now proceed by changing the columns of \(\bf A\) left to right to reduce \(\bf A\) to the form {@upper@},</p><p>where \(n\) can be any number. This form is called upper triangular.<br></p><p>First we swap row 1 and row 2.</p><p>\[{@A@} {@I@} R1 \leftrightarrow R2 \longrightarrow {@matrixa@} {@I2@}. \]</p><p>Now we subtract {@a[2,1]@} times row 1 from row 2 and {@a[3,1]@} times row 1 from row 3.</p><p>\[{@matrixa@} {@I2@} R2 - {@a[2,1]@} R1, R3 - {@a[3,1]@} R1 \longrightarrow&nbsp;{@matrixb@} {@I3@}.\]<br></p><p>Then we divide row 2 by {@b[2,2]@} and subtract {@b[3,2]@} times row 2 from row 3.</p><p>\[{@matrixb@} {@I3@} R2/{@b[2,2]@}, R3 - {@b[3,2]@} R2 \longrightarrow {@matrixc@} {@I4@}.\]<br></p><p>Finally we divide row 3 by {@c[3,3]@}.</p>\[{@matrixc@} {@I4@} R3/{@c[3,3]@} \longrightarrow {@matrixd@} {@I5@}.\]<p></p><p>We would usually proceed by changing the columns of \(\bf A\) right to left to reduce \(\bf A\) to the form {@I@}. However, for this question we already obtained zeros above the main diagonal after we swapped row 1 and row 2.<br></p><p>So we have,</p><p>\[\bf A^{-1} = {@I5@}.\]</p><p><br></p><p>The method can be used to determine \(\bf B^{-1}\) similarly, which gives \( B^{-1} = {@ta2@}.\)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
